'''Kraków School of Mathematics''' ({{lang-pl|krakowska szkoła matematyczna}}) was a sub-group of [[Polish School of Mathematics]] represented by mathematicians from the [[Kraków]] universities—[[Jagiellonian University]] and the [[AGH University of Science and Technology]], active during the [[interwar period]] (1918–1939). Their area of study was primarily [[classical analysis]], [[differential equation]]s and [[analytic function]]s.
The Kraków School of Differential Equations was founded by [[Tadeusz Ważewski]], a student of [[Stanisław Zaremba (mathematician)|Stanisław Zaremba]], and was internationally appreciated after [[World War II]]. The Kraków School of Analytic Functions was founded by [[Franciszek Leja]]. Other notable members includes [[Kazimierz Żorawski]], [[Władysław Ślebodziński]], [[Stanisław Gołąb]] and [[Czesław Olech]].
